textDisplay:
Wrong, wrong, wrong. The problem is we are applying 20th century central-station generation (monopoly) business models to renewable energies, and "the ubiquitous nature of renewable energy argues for a decentralist energy approach." Large transmission creates dis-economies of scale, but it certainly makes Wall Street energy corporations rich building and operating them. There are proven (now over two decades old) equitable policy mechanisms (see Germany's Renewable Sources Act, the Erneuerbare-Energien-Gesetz-EEG, from 2000, for example) that democratize energy, so that everyone may participate equally and meaningfully in energy production. But, as ignorant Americans we ignore them. "The big mistake in the energy debate is that most people think . . . including governments, including many scientists, who get their orders for studies from [the energy companies], they believe and think that the present energy suppliers, the present energy trusts, the companies, they should organize the transformation. And this is a big mistake--a big mistake--because this part of the society is the only one who has an interest to postpone it. . . . All others . . . have an interest to speed it up. But as long as government thinks that it should be left to the energy companies, we will lose the race against time."
--Hermann Scheer Ph.D (1944-2010), on Democracy NOW!, Friday October 10, 2010. Hermann Scheer was a German economist / member of the German Parliament for three decades, president of EUROSOLAR, chairman of the World Council for Renewable Energy (WCRE), president of the International Parliamentary Forum on Renewable Energies, and author.

textDisplay: One big problem that exist are "investor owned utilities". Much like PG & E, other investor owned utilities pay money back to investors stocks before they invest in their infrastructure. This leads to higher consumer prices for power, less investment in the actual system and therefore more catastrophic failures. Electrical CO-OPs on the other hand while not perfect focus more attention on the electrical system they own and maintain. Being member owned they do not have stockholders to pay back. Profits are invested back into the system with equipment upgrades, line rebuilds, etc.

textDisplay: I worked with the best solar engineers in the field from countries worldwide under contact to the government during the Carter administration. The simple, condensed version of their finding was there is an extremely high degradation of electrical energy when transported over lines. The solution is off the grid, rooftop solar supplemented, where possible, with a local wind generation and passive solar throughout the building. No new grid, no new transmission lines, no permission or agreement from anyone. The biggest requirement is need for better, cheaper storage. Nothing has changed. The solution is as solid today as it was then. Unfortunately, that means no income for power companies. We all need to self-generate off the grid, and give the middle finger to everyone who wants to pollute the planet and make money off us while doing it.

textDisplay: As I understand it, Tesla wanted to make electricity free.  He ostensibly knew how to distribute power without stringing wires all over,  but was suppressed by money interests who stood to profit through creation of the inefficient and vulnerable power system that we're still saddled with a hundred years hence.  Either rebuilding antiquated power grid technology or developing other technology will require massive investment.  If the profit motive prevails now as it did then, resources will go towards maintaining the status quo.  Last Week Tonight is fun to watch, although it tends to bypass the elephant in the room, in this case by presenting rebuilding the power grid as the self-evident path forward.

textDisplay:
In Denmark we buried our power cables in the cities a long time ago. We started in the 70's and I think we buried the last in early 90's (maybe late 80's). Granted, Denmark is a small country but our parliament agreed that this is the way to do it. So we did it one step at a time. If you want to see a power cable you have to go to a power station. We do have some large power towers crossing our country but they connect the large cities.

Our neighbourhood had three blackouts this year and they all were fixed in half an hour to an hour. One were human error (cutting a power line) and the other two were faulty equipment at various places (connection boxes). One were right outside my house. I get a text message when such a thing happens.

textDisplay:
Stan for Tesla.

Read any of his patents for his inventions and the true intelligence and character of Tesla becomes mentally palatable.

In my opinion one of the major reasons for their break was Edison's desire to charge for electricity and Tesla's Dream to give everyone in the world free power.

The Tesla Coil's low voltage emissions was a proto-type for a system of electricity that would allow low voltage impulses, world wide, in order to allow anyone anywhere to plug in their devices.

My Inventions by Nikola Tesla and the history based on Primary Sources between Edison and Tesla would be nice to know.

Also the invention of the Florescent Lightbulb, the light bulb that meets energy standards for 2050, and Tesla's work with Powdered Mercury used in the original Florescent Lightbulbs, leading to his mental decline.

But this decline of common mental faculties of course lead to designs for a death ray among other inventions of science fiction fantasy.

There is also some very interesting information about the actual life of Edgar Allen Poe that I have read describing him as a functioning member of society rather a madman with tendencies towards alcoholism.

This more common view of Poe feeds into the fantasies of the narrators of Poe's short stories and was publicized by writers of his era.

textDisplay: Moving forward, setting up huge long range wire systems for electrical for long distances is extremely inefficient, requiring larger gauges to transmit over massive distances, displacing residential zones, and requiring massive amounts of copper, steel, and rubber (which is not going to keep up with demand as rubber crops are struggling more every year, they’ll cut down the whole amazon and plant rubber trees for this kind of thing) and so on. For this conversation to be realistic about the demand, we need to know that longer distances between power supplies is a bad idea. Localize the energy. Not centralize. I also wish this even once mentioned anything at all about next gen nuclear systems. Thorium, fusion, and microplants have come a looong way in the past decade. There are even systems that reuse spent radioactive fuel, and the pelletized thorium fuel could be exported to even the most volatile warring nations, as it cannot be weaponized. Fusion would produce no waste and has had massive developments in success because of the superconductor film mit just made. I’m just a guy with an offgrid solar system living in a yurt. I just want this faux environmentalism to stop. We need nuclear. I know they tell you it’s scary, like how fox shows you Mr. Burns and Homer at the plant, the shows are all about what can go wrong, not even talking about what solutions have become available. R&d. Molten salt thorium reactors. Micro hydro. Personal off grid renewables instead of centralized grids. This is what I would like to see.

textDisplay: I think the obvious was missed here. Why are we spending a lot of money creating huge power grids and infrastructure to move the power instead of investing in covering existing rooftops with solar. It is really old school thinking that power has to come from some gigantic central source and it definitely presents a security risk. I am about to install solar at my house and I only need about 1/3 of my roof to power everything I have including my electric car. I know in Phoenix grocery stores are covering their parking lots with solar to power the store and create shade for shoppers. They also are covering canals with solar which has the added bonus of saving water. There are lots of creative solutions. Of course this would be fought by the big power companies but we need to look at the future in new ways to survive. Let's invest in local sustainable energy and get out of the archaic mind set of the past.

textDisplay:
I'm retired now, but from 1976 through 2017 almost all of my time I was a high voltage transmission engineer. I did the design and project management for the type of power lines you described in your segment. In summary: on point and good work. :-).
You are correct in that its the Right of Way (ROW) that is the biggest problem. More calendar time is often spent getting the permits than acquiring materials and constructing the line. I can design the needed power line anywhere I can get the ROW to put it. There is one aspect that you did not mention: maintenance and laws. In the NE there are states (E.g. NY) where maintenance is not allowed (by the state regulators) to be put into the rate base. I.e. if a utility wants to replace the "hooks" or shackles or cracked insulators for a line it can do so but must "eat the cost" and this is an expense that is never reimbursed through rates to its customers - it comes out of the Bottom Line (profits). So, often the CEO will simply refuse to do so and take his chances on major problems not occurring before he get his bonuses and retirement package. Federal law could change this and allow all utilities to put maintenance charges into the rate base and then the lines would be more reliable. Also, anyone, in a building, who declares some opposition to power lines should have the lights turned off, and the heating and ventilating turned off. We could then say, "Oh dear! The power lines weren't able to take the load the tens or hundreds of miles from the power plants to this building." Do you think its important?

textDisplay:
I work in the power industry, and one thing they didn't mention that is really important is the scarcity/long lead times associated with large transformers. These things often take a year just to build one, so if a large transformer goes down, a station and be out of commission for months/a year depending on availability of emergency replacements.

Another interesting thing I'm surprised they didn't mention is green hydrogen pipelines. Using a device called an electrolyzer (basically a hydrogen fuel cell in reverse), we can use water and electricity to make hydrogen gas, pipe it over long distances (which is cheaper than transmission lines in terms of construction and energy density for operation btw), and use a fuel cell to make clean electricity at the end location such as a large city. Super interesting concept, and also has tons of applications for green hydrogen vehicles/transportation as well.

A really cool concept (which is the one my research is currently in) is load following on distribution feeders. By using large loads like electrolyzers to make green hydrogen fuel (better than batteries btw, not biased bc I work for a Fuel cell company or anything lol), flywheel storage systems, or batteries, we can stabilize the grid when renewable production drops off by ramping down the storage consumption (or even feeding back into the grid if required). This stuff is all really expensive though, and at the moment only flywheels have been made at a scale large enough to matter so we desperately need to pass an infrastructure bill with funding for this kind of research/implementation. Otherwise our grid cannot continue to operate, especially with the challenges posed by renewable energy.

textDisplay:
Engineering is Human
See the engineering bombs! The balloons and rings will drive you mad. That is the artists' integrity and the engineers' measure. Knowing when to let it rest is a hard bit of form and function and good taste depends on the engineer's eye. Quality is not a crime. Legalize silversmithing. Quality is a vast tradition and no place for the uneducated who will fail under its difficult psychology. Engineering is a human experience and a necessary cause. It is underrated and vastly complex. How would they like a world without it running through trees for drama and friddely-bits? They should see, yes, they should see like Scrooge saw for Marley! The truth is that most do not have the integrity for both its truths and secrecy and they bury it selling this human experience like conflict and mortality are an art form. Engineering is human! C'mon. What would you do without daddy? You want to know what happens to your war when engineering pulls the plug? Jacob's Engineering (R) happens and it's empty. You think you'll man it, don't you? You can't brief two-thousand years of engineering breakthroughs. I've been in here for 15 years every day just trying to get a grasp on ringsmithing and I've just scratched the surface. Good luck, man.
textOriginal:
*Engineering is Human*
See the engineering bombs!  The balloons and rings will drive you mad.  That is the artists' integrity and the engineers' measure.    Knowing when to let it rest is a hard bit of form and function and good taste depends on the engineer's eye.  Quality is not a crime.  Legalize silversmithing.  Quality is a vast tradition and no place for the uneducated who will fail under its difficult psychology.  Engineering is a human experience and a necessary cause.  It is underrated and vastly complex.  How would they like a world without it running through trees for drama and friddely-bits?  They should see, yes, they should see like Scrooge saw for Marley!  The truth is that most do not have the integrity for both its truths and secrecy and they bury it selling this human experience like conflict and mortality are an art form.  Engineering is human!  C'mon.  What would you do without daddy?  You want to know what happens to your war when engineering pulls the plug?  Jacob's Engineering (R) happens and it's empty.  You think you'll man it, don't you?  You can't brief two-thousand years of engineering breakthroughs.  I've been in here for 15 years every day just trying to get a grasp on ringsmithing and I've just scratched the surface.  Good luck, man.

textDisplay:
FERC was basically designed to sidestep NIMBY. By streamlining the process of laying down pipelines, mostly by stacking FERC with former oil execs, the idea was to act before any grassroots protests could organize. These grassroots groups have gotten more nimble in the age of the internet, and have had a fair amount of success in places like New York and Massachusetts in stopping unneeded pipeline development. Unfortunately, they've also pushed back against needed power infrastructure, such as the protest against the offshore wind project near Martha's Vineyard.

That's the element that Last Week Tonight misses - renewable energy sources are now being built in areas where power production had not traditionally been built - namely in places that aren't poor. Protests against LNG pipelines in Massachusetts failed in two places - Roxbury and Waymouth - both poor areas, both protests against the danger and toxicity of LNG pipelines and facilities. Martha's Vineyard protested that a wind farm would ruin the view - in other words, the rich don't want to pay the actual cost of electricity, they just want to use it.
textOriginal:
FERC was basically designed to sidestep NIMBY.  By streamlining the process of laying down pipelines, mostly by stacking FERC with former oil execs, the idea was to act before any grassroots protests could organize. These grassroots groups have gotten more nimble in the age of the internet, and have had a fair amount of success in places like New York and Massachusetts in stopping unneeded pipeline development.  Unfortunately, they've also pushed back against needed power infrastructure, such as the protest against the offshore wind project near Martha's Vineyard.  

That's the element that Last Week Tonight misses - renewable energy sources are now being built in areas where power production had not traditionally been built - namely in places that aren't poor.  Protests against LNG pipelines in Massachusetts failed in two places - Roxbury and Waymouth - both poor areas, both protests against the danger and toxicity of LNG pipelines and facilities.  Martha's Vineyard protested that a wind farm would ruin the view - in other words, the rich don't want to pay the actual cost of electricity, they just want to use it.

textDisplay: I don't know what's worse: non connected brand new solar and wind grids, or having the entire USA without any electricity because all their power grids have hit their coffins. At least in France, we have the entirety of our power grid regulated by a single agency (Electricity of France, or EDF), and a few smaller companies on a regional level. Any time we do have a power outage, repair teams are already on the starting blocks to get into action as soon as it happens.

textDisplay: Some very good points... but some key questions left unanswered. For example, why are we still fixated on having our power travel through suspended, unprotected cables held up by giant metal structures, when alternatives exist? Why do we keep phrasing the issue as coal/gas vs renewables, when modern nuclear is safe, efficient, and relatively cheap? (No, I'm not talking about old nuclear, like Chernobyl, Three Mile Island, Fukushima... modern designs are entirely different, just as your current TV is nothing like the one someone was watching in the late 50s.) Why aren't more buildings whose roofs are doing absolutely nothing but keeping the top enclosed not being built with more solar by default (sure, it might not be as efficient, but if 60% of buildings have it, that's still a heck of a lot of power)? And why are we still allowing publicly traded privately owned companies who care more about profit than whether their ancient cable-supporting hooks are wearing through to administer such a vital necessity as power?

textDisplay: Another hurdle will be designing a renewable grid that can meet demand at an instant. Renewables like wind and solar depend on weather and daylight hours, so it is very likely that there is a surge in demand at the same time there is no wind and no sun. It would also be a challenge to balance the grid with a majority of renewable energy. Right now, there are specific generation plants that can come online very quickly when demand spikes at 6pm. This is important because the grid is delicate, there has to be as much being produced as is being consumed at the same instant or else the grid will go down. I think we do need more renewable energy, but it will take coordination of many sectors and collaboration of a lot of smart people to make it work.

textDisplay:
In eastern Pennsylvania, EPA regulations have caused dozens of coal-fired power plants to close over the last 2 decades.
At the same time, we saw an explosion of growth in housing developments, shopping centers, and corporate business parks all increasing demand on the local grid.
The power companies are doing well because they are maximizing return on capital with the remaining natural gas turbine and nuclear plants. Peak power is made from trash burning incinerators.
I'm not saying that closing all the coal plants wasn't all bad. Our rivers have cleaned up now that the ash isn't leaching arsenic and mercury into our watersheds, but we are in a precarious situation because our remaining power plants constantly run at 100% capacity.

We now see brownouts during periods of hot weather or extremely cold weather when HVAC systems are running full-bore.
Our grid certainly can't handle the additional demand of transportation (EV cars and trucks) unless we start addressing the need to build more power plants.
textOriginal:
In eastern Pennsylvania, EPA regulations have caused dozens of coal-fired power plants to close over the last 2 decades. 
At the same time, we saw an explosion of growth in housing developments, shopping  centers, and corporate business parks all increasing demand on the local grid.

I'm not saying that closing all the coal plants wasn't all bad. Our rivers have cleaned up now that the ash isn't leaching arsenic and mercury into our watersheds, but we are in a precarious situation because our remaining power plants constantly run at 100% capacity. 

We now see brownouts during periods of hot weather or extremely cold weather when HVAC systems are running full-bore. 
Our grid certainly can't handle the additional demand of transportation (EV cars and trucks) unless we start addressing the need to build more power plants.

textDisplay:
The tower that looks like a jester is just a tower - it carries 6 groups of conductors. I like powerline towers and I saw one being built in an emergency - those guys are heroes cause the tower must be built to the top and then the bolts and nuts are tightened. It gets shaky up there ...

His point about return on investment is correct. There's a problem though: cost. What's the cost of not doing it - something, unfortunately, the lady failed to mention. Why putting green house gases on the atmosphere costs nothing? Canada thinks it should cost and created a carbon fee - a fee companies pay for how much carbon they put in the atmosphere. The fee is then collected and given back to Canadians - in cash. But why? That doesn't seem to work! Well ... it does! See, Canadians love bacon and to make bacon you need pigs. Pigs, like any animal, produce crap - a lot of it. The pigs crap then ferments and methane is put in the atmosphere - even though methane has a single carbon atom, it is equivalent - in green house effects - to 20 CO2 molecules. If you burn a methane molecule it produces one CO2 molecule and 2 H20 molecules - in other words, it's the equivalent of removing 19 molecules of CO2 from the atmosphere.

Back to bacon! I'm a nice guy and I care about the future and don't want humanity to end on a nuclear winter caused by mass migrations cause by climate change so I collect my pigs' crap, ferment it and use the methane to heat the baby pigs. However, it's actually a bit more expensive for me to do so and my bacon does not sell that well because of the higher price. Now, in Canada, the guy that doesn't do what I do will have an extra cost - the Carbon Fee - and his bacon will sell less than mine. The Carbon Fee does not remove money from the economy and does not reduce the purchasing power of citizens - it just makes my bacon cheaper and then more people buy it and I get ... what? A better return on investment.

Hire me, John. I'm cat who doesn't care if people forget my birthday. And the better return on investment I get was only made possible because there was a price put on a resource - the atmosphere, in this case. Attaching a price or cost to resources is the line taken by, AFAIK, most Green Parties in the world.

Why putting green house gases on the atmosphere costs nothing? Canada thinks it should cost and created a carbon fee - a fee companies pay for how much carbon they put in the atmosphere. The fee is then collected and given back to Canadians - in cash. But why? That doesn't seem to work! Well ... it does! See, Canadians love bacon and to make bacon you need pigs. Pigs, like any animal, produce crap - a lot of it. The pigs crap then ferments and methane is put in the atmosphere - even though methane has a single carbon atom, it is equivalent - in green house effects - to 20 CO2 molecules. If you burn a methane molecule it produces one CO2 molecule and 2 H20 molecules - in other words, it's the equivalent of removing 19 molecules of CO2 from the atmosphere.

Back to bacon! I'm a nice guy and I care about the future and don't want humanity to end on a nuclear winter caused by mass migrations cause by climate change so I collect my pigs' crap, ferment it and use the methane to heat the baby pigs. However, it's actually a bit more expensive for me to do so and my bacon does not sell that well because of the higher price. Now, in Canada, the guy that doesn't do what I do will have an extra cost - the Carbon Fee - and his bacon will sell less than mine. The Carbon Fee does not remove money from the economy and does not reduce the purchasing power of citizens - it just makes my bacon cheaper and then more people buy it and I get ... what? A better return on investment. 

Hire me, John. I'm cat who doesn't care if people forget my birthday. And the better return on investment I get was only made possible because there was a price put on a resource - the atmosphere, in this case. Attaching a price or cost to resources is the line taken by, AFAIK, most Green Parties in the world.

textDisplay:
Don't underestimate the Midwest farmer. Farmers know about the importance of electricity and money. I saw an episode of a show called "Last Week Tonight" on HBO where a British dude tells about how it was Roosevelt's Rural Electrification Plan that made electricity accessible to the common people. You add to that the fact the farmer will get money from installing that wind mill and you won't have problems. You'll have problems were you have problems: open capital companies - those with stocks being traded. The company that did not do preventive maintenance on a power line did it (or didn't do it) because that would affect the next trimester profits. You know why Germany has so many industries? It's because over 50% of those companies are owned by families or partners and are not open capital companies. A family or partners can think about the future and decide to reduce or even zero profits now in exchange for a better financial future.

So, stop bad mouthing the guy that grows your bacon, corn and turkey.

BTW, The Grid is called Grid because it's ... a grid. You don't need to build powerlines from the production centers to consumers - you need to connect producers to the power grid. Of course it's not that simple - the grid must support the power transmission. Old powerlines will be kept and new ones will be built besides them - aluminum cables have not improved because it's still aluminum. There's one basic high school problem to solve: loss of energy by heat or ohmic loss. That one is easy and as we all know (or should know) connecting two resistors in parallel results on a resistance smaller than the smallest of the two resistances. This is important because ohmic loss is proportional to the square of the current (somethin I would not expect everybody to know, btw) and if I have two parallel transmission lines I can send some current on one and the remainder on the other one. There's another problem, though: those are transmission lines and this means they are oscillators and that imposes some weird problems that nowadays can be managed and predicted - as long as parts made to last 50 years are not left in place for 100 years.

Oh ... one more point, John: electric cars don't clean the planet. Clean energy does. Li-Ion batteries are actually important pollutants since they use heavy metals on their composition. I understand, you were talking about green house gases which, btw, electric cars do nothing to solve unless the electricity they use is clean.

textDisplay:
Nuclear, nuclear, nuclear!

I’m a huge fan of renewables and will be putting solar on my house, but we need a stable, consistent backbone that can be placed anywhere, and that’s nuclear. Renewables are great for peak usage, but nuclear power is stable, highly efficient, and just as safe as renewables. Build times are coming down with five years for a new plant of older design, and two years for the next-gen smaller reactors, with the new reactors costing five hundred million to one billion (a fraction of the cost of old-design reactors).

We need to get smart as a country and take the nuclear+renewables path. We could be self-sufficient and off fossil fuels in 15-20 years, and possibly sooner if we streamlined the bureaucracy around nuclear the way France has already done.

textDisplay: I'm not against wind energy. I'm not offended by the presence of a wind turbine. But I was driving through another part of the state a while ago, and in any direction you looked, it was turbines as far as you could see. Not along a desolate stretch of interstate where there were no homes. In any direction there were 15-25 turbines in your field of view, some close, some far. Even though there were trees, and towns, they are massive and you can see them for miles. I've got no problem with a wind turbine going into a field right next to me... If I stood in my yard and there were two or three in sight if I looked all around, I'd be fine with that. ...but having them dominate the landscape is not what I signed up for when I bought my house. It feels like wind energy fights to come into a county, and if they manage to do it, they plant as many as they possibly can. ...so instead of spreading them around, people either have to chose between fighting tooth and nail to keep them out, or live in a wind turbine zone. As people see what happens to a county when they get their foot in the door, they'll start to fight harder to keep them out making the issue worse. Probably need to get some laws in place.

textDisplay: While I agree with Mr. Oliver's point that we do need more lines and upgrades I think this is a gross oversimplification of how things work crossing THAT many properties. For example: I live in middle of no where hodunk Indiana on a 25 house cul-de-sac. By county law there cannot be more than 25 houses on that cul-de-sac without a second access road. After 3 hearings begging for an access road, a new development went in to put in 50 new houses on our deadend cul-de-sac without an access road. County's rarely abide by the laws they made and to sue them would sink months of your life and years of pay in lawyer fees. So, there are very real reasons why country people don't want to deal with any of this that go beyond simply being selfish

textDisplay: Hi Jon, I usually love everything about your shows, but you have missed a really big point in this one. While fossil fuel plants can be built anywhere, the fuel does not just appear magically on their doorstep. The system for bringing the energy to them is even more onerous than for electricity. Either it has to come via pipeline or truck, and this infrastructure has even more issues than power lines. By omitting this fact, you leave a false impression of a difficulty for renewables that fossil fuels does not have.

textDisplay: Great episode and a topic I was just discussing with my family for more energy storage and transfer. Canada and Mexico might also be good investments for energy trade helping neighbors set up grids and trade back and forth depending on need. I really want John to do a piece on animal shelters, especially government run and police departments, for poor conditions and lack of funding/motivation for programs reducing euthanasia rates and more importantly increase quality of life for the animals they are there to protect(otherwise they are less shelters and more prisons). That issue is close to me and I feel would help people care for animals as more than property. Early laws were only to help reduce cattle and horse losses in transit and quickly turned around to favor children being mistreated as property giving them rights while animals were put off for another time. We do not need domestic animals to live, but humans did domesticate them from nature for profit and equated that to survival for ourselves over the products well being. Most of the time people do take care of their pets and that helps the fatigue, but they are still considered inferior to humans making management focus on what is best for people(money and dogs not biting) and not the animals(positive reinforcment and low stress environments). Please look into compassion fatigue/burnout for volunteers and employees, mismanagement, TNR programs, jurisdictions lacking funding, transparency, and the necessity of certified behaviorists and trainers teaching employees and volunteers about proper animal care with positive reinforcment. Sorry for the virtue signaling and guilt over current aninal welfare, but save rates do not make a shelter "good" when they discriminate breeds and behaviors that all can be managed with more resources like rescues, community outreach, donations/better funding(the city shelter I worked at was last on the Public Works funding list puttin the human prisons first and aninal prisons last), and education from professionals, not just the few employees who uncertified managers trained or went to one introductory behavior/training course. That's my little rant and I hope there are animal lovers or other  current and former shelter/police department employees/volunteers/rescues who agree with my sentiment.

textDisplay: The problem is centralized electricity systems. The solution is not “make more centralized electricity systems”. We need autonomy for individual users. All upgrading our power grid will do is kick the problem down the line another 100 years and keep the the energy moguls profiting. We need small scale micro power plants to augment our existing system. The only reason upgrading our power lines will be expensive to fix is because they are trying to convince the people to pay for replacing their profit machines. We can just fix the mechanical issues with our existing power grids if their power load being drawn off them is massively reduced by strategic small scale green power systems within cities and neighborhoods. We need to create redundancy while upgrading the safety of our existing grid. Much of the issues with the old grid is that we are over drawing on those lines. Line loss is directly current dependent. The power you draw at a constant voltage the more current you draw. And we’ve approached the limits of our thickness of line for the power being drawn/current draw. We still will need the grid to help smooth out supply but if people’s power is coming from near them and not being sent to them the lines don’t need to be upgraded. Stop letting the energy monopolies convince the American people to pay for these mega corps profit machines. Help the actual people not need to rely on those centralized systems. Otherwise we are just being duped with another get rich scheme by these energy corporations.

textDisplay:
I just dont understand why the conversation is not about less grid dependency (i.e. power storage, power banks for homes with solar). Investing in improving battery technology and capacity. Improving home and home appliance efficiency.

The same arguments he's making in support of shoring-up the grid, and similar comments below this video are the same arguments many people would make for the keystone pipeline. There is no push to lessen RELIANCE on the grid because the power companies will not profit as much from it.

For this to work you are talking about thousands of miles of high density copper transmission lines. Thousands of steel towers erected, in places like national parks. All that raw material will need to come from somewhere, mined with heavy diesel equipment. The materials will likely come from places like china that will not follow the same climate goals.

We should be talking about hydrogen, solar and other renewables. A lot of people argue that hydrogen is not safe or is not efficient to create. But we are already talking about increasing energy use with this strategy and changing the ladscape of our country.

We wont talk about hydrogen because it's too easy for people to use it off the grid and not depend on the power company. The same goes for solar; because you cannot charge someone to use a piece of the sun, solar technology will never see its fullest potential.

textDisplay:
Approx 18 mins - ROI: That’s such a Republican capitalistic attitude.
And that’s a major reason the grid in in such bad shape.
When I was young, electric companies and most utilities were considered safe and conservative investments.
The theory at the time was that some things were too important to be left to the vagaries of the market.
Then the new breed of Republican capitalists started pushing deregulation—for just about everything.
And what happened?
Just about every time, consumer costs dropped for a short time, and then the costs went up.
But, something else happened that was generally overlooked—-The new owners in these industries almost always dropped their investment in the business.

Look at your electric bill. The cost for your power usage is typically among the lowest items on the bill.
Every individual and separate owner of a piece of the grid wants its share.
Meanwhile, power companies have merely a fraction of the support and repair staff they used to.
Next time, your area has a massive outage after a storm or something, listen to the news for how many crews have been deployed and where they are from. They run lean; don’t pay as well as they used to; in minor emergencies, they call in crews from other states.

Eventually, this profits first attitude is going to bite us as a nation. But, their attitude is “well, that’s just a worst case scenario. We’ll be fine..”

Maybe.

textDisplay:
As serious as climate change is,, attempting to convert all current energy use to 100% renewable energy sources will be disastrous due to the immense amount of raw minerals required for this transition. Mining operations (such as Cobalt in the Congo) have high costs to human and environmental health. Besides the sheer amount of minerals required to convert to "100% renewable" at current rates of consumption exceed reserves that would be economically extractable.

This discussion needs to be reframed to focus on what it will take to reduce energy consumption dramatically in developed nations (yes it will require huge changes to our way of life), and FIRST invest in poorer nations who are suffering the effects of climate change more severely despite not being responsible for most emissions.

I recommend this video for more data on mineral resource depletion: https://youtu.be/DU6gWZav2T8
